Most women feel that frequent urination during early pregnancy can be overcome by taking in lesser fluids. However, it is not a healthy practice as fluids are essential for the developing foetus.

The growth of your baby is incredibly fast at this juncture. It is an embryo right now, about the size of a sesame seed and resembles a tadpole more than a human baby. There is a lot of activity going in there with the neural tube developing and the heart dividing into various chambers and creating a fully developed circulatory system. 

Ectoderm, mesoderm and endoderm are the three layers that are composing it. The ectoderm houses the neural tube, from which the spinal cord, backbone, nerves will sprout. The mesoderm will house the heart and the circulatory system and the endoderm would provide room to your baby’s lungs, intestines, liver, pancreas etc. The placenta and the umbilical cord are fully functional by now. 

Though your pregnancy is not showing now, you can feel it now due to the pregnancy discomforts. However, learn to cope up with them as those would be there for the coming few weeks at least!

Pregnancy will probably make you more sensitive to odors, tastes, strong fragrances, touch, and sudden movements. Try showering and brushing your teeth more frequently and, in general, using care in your life. However, for some women, the increased sensitivity may make foods or lovemaking more enjoyable.

You are now in the beginning stage or first trimester as per development method calculations. This is generally counted from your last menstrual period (LMP) to 12 weeks. The embryo develops all the major organs, becomes a fetus, and the placenta takes over control in your first trimester. You are probably experiencing morning sickness. Eating smaller meals more frequently can be a great help.
